# Spec discipline

`docs/SPEC.md` is the contract; code and spec must agree.

## SPEC-first (§21.2)
- Behavior-changing work updates `docs/SPEC.md` first. If code and spec conflict, surface it before coding.
- For new behavior, propose the spec change, get approval, then implement.

## Preserve IDs (§21.1)
- `FR/NFR/AC/UC/AD/OQ` IDs are stable and append-only. Never renumber, delete, or reuse.
- New requirements take the next free number; deprecate in place, do not delete.
- Architecture decisions live in `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` (`AD-xxx`); an AD that changes behavior must
  also be reflected in `docs/SPEC.md`.

## Traceability (§21.13, AC-027)
- Cite the requirement ID in each test name/comment (e.g. `// FR-054`).
- Update the matching `docs/traceability.md` row in the same change that implements a requirement.
- Before finishing, run `python harness/scripts/check_traceability.py` and `python harness/scripts/check_engine_parity.py`.

## Engine authority & semantics (NFR-004, §21.3, §21.4)
- The Transon engine is authoritative for validation/execution; Blockly constraints improve UX but
  never replace it. Do not invent rule behavior — consult the engine metadata/source.

## Escalate security ambiguity (§21.11)
- Changes touching engine execution, sandboxing, `file` writes, `include` loading, remote examples,
  or user-data transmission are security-sensitive — propose a spec update and use the
  `round-trip-review` skill.
